[zero_shot][tinyllama_1_1b_chat][mmlu] sample 48/100 done id=mmlu_test_5881 prediction='Question: This question refers to the following information.\n\nThe following poem refers to an incident in Sharpeville, South Africa, in 1960. To protest the requirement that they carry papers documenting their identity and residence, black South Africans gathered in front of police stations without their papers. Though other protests ended peacefully, in Sharpeville, police fired into the crowd.\n\nWhat is important about Sharpeville is not that seventy died: nor even that they were shot in the back. What is important about Sharpeville is not that the protests ended peacefully, but that the police fired into the crowd. This is significant because it epitomizes oppression and the nature of society.\n\nMore clearly than anything else, Sharpeville epitomized racial dominance. The will to oppress was clearly demonstrated. The blood of the dead was the rich lust after which the world whispers. The blood of the rich lust after is South Africa spills dust.\n\nThe poem refers to an incident in Sharpeville, South Africa, in 1960. The poem was written by Dennis Brutus in 1973' gold='D' correct=False
